The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 IOC ready for Haldia

 A STAFF REPORTER

 Calcutta, Sept. 5: Indian Oil Corporation (IOC) has formally agreed to be the anchor investor in the chemical hub at Haldia.

 IOC has informed the government that its board has approved the decision. A formal agreement between the oil company and the state government would be inked soon, a government official said.

 The issue will be discussed at a meeting of the cabinet committee on industry tomorrow.

 After a formal approval by the cabinet committee, the government will apply to the Centre for Haldias Petroleum Chemicals and Petrochemical Investment Region (PCPIR) status. Were roping in ILFS and Mott McDonald to prepare a master plan of the area, detailing the infrastructure there, said a commerce and industries department official.

 IOC had earlier said it plans to invest around Rs 15,000 crore in Haldia.

 Japanese consul-general Yoshikazu Takeuchi met PWD minister Kshiti Goswami today and expressed displeasure over the handing of the Raichak-Kukrahati bridge project to the Indonesian Salim Group while the Japanese were already conducting a feasibility study for it. 

 We have asked the Japanese to continue the survey for the bridge on the river Haldi. So far, we havent received any order from the government to scrap our agreement (with the Japanese), the minister said after the meeting.




